Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, I want to discuss with you today the builds

00:55.580 --> 00:59.600
approved by the Senate Judiciary Committee and sponsored by Senator William General of

00:59.600 --> 01:03.540
Indiana and John Marshall Butler of Maryland.

01:03.540 --> 01:07.500
These bills result from disagreement with Supreme Court decisions.

01:07.500 --> 01:13.180
They seek to overturn the decisions in various ways by limiting the jurisdiction of the court

01:13.180 --> 01:17.420
or by broadly rewriting statutes which the court has interpreted.

01:17.420 --> 01:19.500
I think they are very dangerous legislation.

01:19.500 --> 01:23.900
I have hoarded against them and I shall oppose them on the floor of the Senate.

01:23.900 --> 01:28.040
I doubt it bears a person in the United States who agrees with every decision the Supreme

01:28.040 --> 01:29.040
Court makes.

01:29.040 --> 01:35.820
Certainly, the justices do not always agree, sometimes split as five to four even among them.

01:35.820 --> 01:38.860
And neither do I always agree with the majority.

01:38.860 --> 01:43.020
Nevertheless, we made a decision in this country a long, long time ago.

01:43.020 --> 01:47.860
And that decision was that we would have three coordinated branches of government, the

01:47.860 --> 01:52.900
executive, the legislative, and the judicial, each acting as a check on the other.

01:52.900 --> 01:58.020
And I will be no party to the destruction or seriously crippling of any of these three.

01:58.020 --> 02:02.500
I do not have time to discuss with you fully all the implications of these amendments.

02:02.500 --> 02:06.420
Why would Senators General and Butler sought to do with their amendments?

02:06.420 --> 02:12.740
Why is to undo 150 years of legislative and judicial history with a sweep of the pen and

02:12.740 --> 02:15.580
without even waiting for adequate hearings?

02:15.580 --> 02:21.180
The bill denies a pellet jurisdiction to the Supreme Court over any law, rule, or regulation

02:21.180 --> 02:25.340
pertaining to admission of persons to practice law within the state.

02:25.340 --> 02:30.300
This results from disagreement with a decision in which a person who was a former communist

02:30.300 --> 02:35.700
but who had their repented was denied admission to the bar in New Mexico.

02:35.700 --> 02:40.360
It is not whether that the man who secluded the motion to deny the admission and who may

02:40.360 --> 02:45.260
have disagreed with the decision expressed his opposition to this bill of the Judiciary

02:45.260 --> 02:50.500
Committee, the president of the American Bar Association opposed it.

02:50.500 --> 02:52.660
The southern there is certainly all to oppose it.

02:52.660 --> 02:58.540
The last time bar membership was denied was by reconstruction governments after the war

02:58.540 --> 03:03.300
between the states and the Supreme Court upheld their right to membership.

03:03.300 --> 03:07.100
And another thing you remember that the only time jurisdiction has been taken away from

03:07.100 --> 03:14.700
the Supreme Court was in some of the Reconstruction Acts which other Congress passed and President

03:14.700 --> 03:16.540
Johnson vetoed.

03:16.540 --> 03:21.000
But the Congress of the United States just a few months after gave the jurisdiction back

03:21.000 --> 03:23.060
to the Supreme Court.

03:23.060 --> 03:28.060
But the most serious thing is that it sets a precedent of limiting jurisdiction to the

03:28.060 --> 03:29.220
Court.

03:29.220 --> 03:33.700
Under this line of reasoning every time you don't like a decision, the thing to do is to take

03:33.700 --> 03:36.820
another bit of jurisdiction away from the Court.

03:36.820 --> 03:39.740
This is a kill the umpire technique.

03:39.740 --> 03:42.420
