21:23.600 --> 21:25.200
Yes, then back one day.

21:25.200 --> 21:29.640
Well, tell us about your trip and how long we're in the Soviet Union and what you find

21:29.640 --> 21:30.640
out about education.

21:30.640 --> 21:36.640
Well, Senator, first thank you for that gracious introduction and I'm glad to greet my friends

21:36.640 --> 21:39.520
in Tennessee on your program.

21:39.520 --> 21:43.160
We had a very intensive schedule.

21:43.800 --> 21:49.800
There were ten of us on this team outstanding the other nine at least were outstanding educators

21:49.800 --> 21:53.000
in the United States, the parties and their field.

21:53.000 --> 21:59.480
We were one of the first teams in the cultural exchange agreement signed between our two

21:59.480 --> 22:01.400
countries.

22:01.400 --> 22:08.040
We were therefore official guests of the Soviet Union and to be a guest of the Soviet Union

22:08.040 --> 22:13.600
is particularly significant because the doors are open and we were privileged to see anything

22:13.600 --> 22:20.680
we wanted to see and we traveled by a special airplane over many thousands of miles.

22:20.680 --> 22:28.240
Well, we went to after our studies in the Moscow area, we went to Kazan and the entire

22:28.240 --> 22:29.640
autonomous republic.

22:29.640 --> 22:35.760
We went over to Severed Lose in the Ural, the Pittsburgh of the Ural, and the Siberia

22:35.760 --> 22:42.240
and then we went down coast to our joining the Chinese border in Kazakistan and Almaha

22:42.240 --> 22:50.120
and then over to Taishkent, New Uzbekistan, alongside of Afghanistan and then over to Sochi

22:50.120 --> 22:51.760
on the Black Sea.

22:51.760 --> 22:53.440
Yes, I had a privilege of going there.

22:53.440 --> 22:54.920
That's the great bathing place.

22:54.920 --> 22:58.200
Yes, but we didn't have much bathing they put us to work.

22:58.200 --> 23:02.480
Well, Laurence, what were your outstanding impressions of these several weeks that you went

23:02.480 --> 23:03.800
all over the Soviet Union?

23:03.800 --> 23:13.000
Well, the outstanding impression of our team of 10 was almost frightening in the sense of

23:13.000 --> 23:18.600
our realization of the total commitment that that nation of 220 million people with their

23:18.600 --> 23:21.200
vast resources are making education.

23:21.200 --> 23:26.840
Well, what talk we saw them making is a real challenge to us here in the United States.

23:26.840 --> 23:36.680
Well, I should say it is that you see not only are there budgets for education adequate,

23:36.680 --> 23:43.280
they're building buildings very rapidly, their equipment is good, but every segment of Soviet

23:43.280 --> 23:46.320
society is tied in with the schools.

23:46.320 --> 23:49.480
That's the one-time thing they're putting emphasis on.

23:49.480 --> 23:53.840
They're betting on education to win the race for supremacists.

23:53.840 --> 23:55.600
And how about the teachers?

23:55.600 --> 23:59.840
When I remember when I was there three years ago I remember they were quite well-tieded.

23:59.840 --> 24:04.560
Yes, teachers are at the top of the scale.

24:04.560 --> 24:06.120
We did a lot of study on that.

24:06.120 --> 24:11.360
They're paid at the same as doctors, medical doctors and engineers.

24:11.360 --> 24:14.160
That is the secondary school teachers.

24:14.160 --> 24:17.000
The elementary teachers are slight nights below.

24:17.000 --> 24:20.200
The university teachers are at the top of the scale.

24:20.200 --> 24:23.040
But the high school teachers are paid as our doctors.

24:23.440 --> 24:29.880
Well, are they placing particular emphasis on science and technology or what about their

24:29.880 --> 24:30.880
general education?

24:30.880 --> 24:37.080
Well, they have a general education that of course emphasizes mathematics and science,

24:37.080 --> 24:40.720
but they also emphasize other fields too.

24:40.720 --> 24:48.160
And recently they're giving emphasis to really industrial education.

24:48.160 --> 24:53.000
Well, are they devoting more of their national budget to education than we are here?

24:53.000 --> 24:56.640
Well, it's very difficult to make that kind of comparison.

24:56.640 --> 25:02.080
I can say that the school people were never concerned and seemed surprised that our questions

25:02.080 --> 25:07.800
about budget, they have the money to pay these top salaries to provide the equipment.

25:07.800 --> 25:14.160
And on top of that industry and other agents are required to contribute.

25:14.160 --> 25:17.080
Well, Commissioner D'Earthick, I know that your friends and tennis players are glad to

25:17.080 --> 25:18.360
see you and to hear your report.

25:18.360 --> 25:21.160
I wish we had more time, but our time has run out.

25:21.160 --> 25:22.560
That's all until next week.

25:22.560 --> 25:23.560
Thank you very much.

25:30.960 --> 25:37.960
Friends, Senator Keith Ober of Tennessee, who was Democratic candidate firm of ice president

25:37.960 --> 25:44.440
of the United States in 1956, is so well known he needs no introduction anywhere in the United

25:44.440 --> 25:45.440
States.

25:45.440 --> 25:48.920
Senator, you and I served in the House of Representatives.

25:48.920 --> 25:53.120
I hope to be with you in the United States Senate, after next January.

25:53.120 --> 25:54.600
I welcome you today.

25:54.600 --> 25:59.440
Well, Steve Young, it certainly has a pleasure to be on this program with you.

25:59.440 --> 26:03.960
I remember so well when I first came to the House of Representatives back in 1940 and

26:03.960 --> 26:06.880
you were an experienced member.

26:06.880 --> 26:12.120
And then after your term then you resigned to go into the armed services of the United

26:12.120 --> 26:17.680
States and then you came back in 1948 and served on the Ways and Means Committee.

26:17.680 --> 26:21.160
I enjoyed the service with you in the House of Representatives.

26:21.160 --> 26:26.280
I think you did an outstanding job for the people of Ohio and the nation.

26:26.280 --> 26:32.240
Always when they, side of the plain people was up and they needed protection with a vote

26:32.240 --> 26:37.160
or needed someone to speak for them, you were always ready and willing to do so.

26:37.160 --> 26:41.520
So that I do hope you'll be with us here in the United States Senate.

26:41.520 --> 26:45.680
We have a lot of very important issues before the people of the United States and the Senate

26:45.680 --> 26:49.520
and your past experience and the House of Representatives.

26:49.520 --> 26:55.800
And I've kept up with your political and economic and social activity since that time will

26:55.800 --> 27:00.160
be of great benefit to the nation and certainly to our democratic cause.

27:00.160 --> 27:04.320
You and I almost invariably voted alike, Senator.

27:04.320 --> 27:09.760
May I ask you what do you consider some of the dominant issues in this campaign?

27:09.760 --> 27:12.680
Well, you talk about us voting alike.

27:12.680 --> 27:18.880
I know we always had the same general philosophy, but maybe you had not say too much about

27:18.880 --> 27:24.360
that, but I remember one thing that you're always in favor of keeping up the defenses of

27:24.360 --> 27:30.000
this nation, of keeping our nation strong and that you voted for appropriations for all

27:30.000 --> 27:36.440
of our armed services in order that we could have adequate strength to defend ourselves.

27:36.440 --> 27:42.400
I think the dominant issues in this campaign, Steve, is you so well know are that this administration

27:42.400 --> 27:46.080
came into power on two big ideas.

27:46.080 --> 27:50.640
First, they could run the business of the country better that they knew a lot about business.

27:50.640 --> 27:53.120
Well, they've failed in that.

27:53.120 --> 27:56.760
We've had more inflation every month by month and we've had the poor.

27:56.760 --> 27:57.760
We have unemployment.

27:57.760 --> 28:00.160
Our factories are not producing.

28:00.160 --> 28:05.440
We have a great deal of suffering and over 5 million people unemployed.

28:05.440 --> 28:11.520
The tight money policy has hurt the small business man, the farmer and people all up and

28:11.520 --> 28:13.200
down the line.

28:13.200 --> 28:19.680
So we need a democratic administration that will expand our economy, keep our people employed

28:19.680 --> 28:27.440
and see that we economically as well as other ways have full productivity.

28:27.440 --> 28:31.880
The Democratic Party has the leadership and the ability to do that and this administration

28:31.880 --> 28:33.960
has shown that it doesn't.

28:33.960 --> 28:41.640
The next second thing is that we supposed to be good in foreign policy, the Republican

28:41.640 --> 28:42.640
administration.

28:42.640 --> 28:45.400
Well, we've lost friends in the Middle East.

28:45.400 --> 28:46.880
We've lost them in South America.

28:46.880 --> 28:53.520
We've lost them in Asia and our North Atlantic Treaty organization has been calling apart

28:53.520 --> 28:56.360
and straining at the bits.

28:56.360 --> 29:02.480
So there isn't any reason why we can't be the leading nation in the world if we have

29:02.480 --> 29:07.440
an enlightened foreign policy that the Democratic Party will bring back.

29:07.440 --> 29:10.080
The two things the Republicans were elected on, they failed.

29:10.080 --> 29:15.040
I think the people know that and they are looking for Democrats like you to come to the United

29:15.040 --> 29:17.320
States Senate and help us get the job done.

29:17.320 --> 29:23.600
Well, of course, involuntary unemployment as you and I both know is a great moral wrong.

29:23.600 --> 29:31.680
And at the same time to have this ever spiraling upward cost of living, of flicking our people,

29:31.680 --> 29:32.680
that is the dominant issue.

29:32.680 --> 29:33.680
I agree with your senator.

29:33.680 --> 29:34.680
That is the dominant.

29:34.680 --> 29:35.680
And there's no reason.

29:35.680 --> 29:38.680
No reason why it should be that way.

29:38.680 --> 29:41.680
The tight money policy of this administration resulted in that.

29:41.680 --> 29:42.680
Good.

29:42.680 --> 29:43.680
We don't believe them.

29:43.680 --> 29:44.680
We have to be with you, old pal.

29:44.680 --> 29:48.680
Glad to see you.

29:48.680 --> 30:01.640
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, as chairman of the political

30:01.640 --> 30:08.080
committee of the NATO Parliamentarians conference, it has become necessary for me to attend a meeting

30:08.080 --> 30:16.600
in Europe this weekend to make plans for the Hague-type Congress of which all 17 NATO nations

30:16.600 --> 30:20.200
will attend and which will be held next year.

30:20.200 --> 30:24.600
I'm leaving Washington Thursday night for the meeting in Paris and will return Sunday

30:24.600 --> 30:25.600
night.

30:25.600 --> 30:29.800
At the meeting will be the president of the NATO Parliamentarians conference, Colonel

30:29.800 --> 30:35.040
Femmes of the Netherlands, Congressman Wayne Hayes of O'Hah, who is vice president

30:35.040 --> 30:40.160
of the conference, representatives of the parliament of all of the other NATO nations

30:40.160 --> 30:42.120
and myself.

30:42.120 --> 30:47.160
Also president will be representative citizens from all of the other NATO nations, distinguished

30:47.160 --> 30:49.840
people who are very much interested.

30:49.840 --> 30:53.440
As you know, NATO will be ten years old next year.

30:53.440 --> 30:58.320
During those ten years it has been the free works bulwark against communism.

30:58.320 --> 31:03.260
This partnership of free nations packs together the power that has made it possible to keep

31:03.260 --> 31:06.400
freedom alive and vibrant on this earth.

31:06.400 --> 31:10.960
Naturally we have not always agreed with all that our allies have done and they have not

31:10.960 --> 31:13.520
always agreed with what we have done.

31:13.520 --> 31:19.800
But together we have weathered many storms which otherwise might have sunk our nations individually.

31:19.800 --> 31:24.760
Next year we will be starting our second decade as a NATO alliance.

31:24.760 --> 31:30.040
At the meeting of the parliamentarians conference last November I sponsored a resolution which

31:30.040 --> 31:34.240
called for this Hig-type Congress in 1959.

31:34.240 --> 31:39.040
I felt that we ought to be planning our second decade and that in these plans we ought not

31:39.040 --> 31:44.120
limit ourselves entirely to the diplomats and representatives of the governments.

31:44.120 --> 31:48.760
We ought to tap the minds and imaginations of the people themselves.

31:48.760 --> 31:51.400
This resolution passed unanimously.

31:51.400 --> 31:57.040
This Congress will be held and the meeting this weekend is to make plans for it to decide

31:57.040 --> 32:03.480
where and when during 1959 it will be held and what will be done to Congress and so on.

32:03.480 --> 32:05.880
I am very excited about its prospects.

32:05.880 --> 32:09.840
There is nothing more important in this world than peace.

32:09.840 --> 32:13.360
Peace like everything else doesn't just happen.

32:13.360 --> 32:18.520
We have to work to bring it about and in the work we will have to tap all of our resources,

32:18.520 --> 32:21.840
all of our people who have contributions to make.

32:21.840 --> 32:27.040
We cannot let small things that divide us overcome the big things that unite us and the

32:27.040 --> 32:32.680
best way to prevent that is to freely discuss among ourselves both our differences and

32:32.680 --> 32:34.480
our aspirations.

32:34.480 --> 32:40.280
I shall tell you more of my observations of this very important meeting next week.

32:40.280 --> 32:45.120
Meanwhile I wanted to add on the domestic side that this past week in Congress has certainly

32:45.120 --> 32:47.080
been a very busy one.

32:47.080 --> 32:51.280
This is the season of the year when we began to see results of a lot of pains taking

32:51.280 --> 32:54.040
work that has gone earlier.

32:54.040 --> 32:58.160
I was pleased with some of the results obtained this last week.

32:58.160 --> 33:02.000
The Senate passed the appropriations bill for public works.

33:02.000 --> 33:08.320
I am happy to say that it included $75,000 to be used as planning money for flood control

33:08.320 --> 33:13.160
work in northwest Tennessee on the Forkett deer and the Obine Rivers where they have had

33:13.160 --> 33:16.680
so much rain and destruction for the last few years.

33:16.680 --> 33:20.040
This has been a very great problem for a number of years.

33:20.040 --> 33:25.040
And now that the local groups are organized it will be possible to get this appropriation

33:25.040 --> 33:30.120
and have the aid of the United States engineers in solving the very great drainage problem

33:30.120 --> 33:32.400
in that part of our state.

33:32.400 --> 33:37.880
Also there was $550,000 appropriation for continuation of the work on the Memphis

33:37.880 --> 33:39.000
Harvard.

33:39.000 --> 33:43.000
This will make possible the completion of the protection necessary on the Tennessee

33:43.000 --> 33:44.000
River.

33:44.000 --> 33:49.160
So that this land, known generally as insulated bottoms, will be available for our industrial

33:49.160 --> 33:50.160
usage.

33:50.160 --> 33:56.400
Also in the bill it was $50,000 for planning work for the Melton Hill Dam to be built

33:56.400 --> 33:59.920
by the TVA on the Flint River near Oak Ridge.

33:59.920 --> 34:04.600
With this money and with the proceeds of the TVA self-financing bill which passed the Senate

34:04.600 --> 34:11.200
last year and which I hope will soon pass the House, TVA will be able to go forward with

34:11.200 --> 34:18.040
this new dam which will mean so much not only for power and navigation but also for recreation

34:18.040 --> 34:21.640
to the people around Oak Ridge and Clinton and Knoxville.

34:21.640 --> 34:24.400
It will be one of the best TVA dams.

34:24.400 --> 34:28.960
Also in the bill was money for the Barclay Dam or the Cheedham work on the Cheedham

34:28.960 --> 34:30.960
Dam and other work on the Cumberland River.

